Please Note: The best model in this notebook is Counter Vectorizer and Logistic Model

1. Overview¶

Build a machine learning model that predicts which Tweets are about real disasters and which ones arent. We have access to a dataset of 10,000 tweets that were hand classified.

4. Dataset preperation¶

Pre processing

  • Tokenization
  • Lowercasing the words
  • Lemmatization/Stemming (shorten words to their root stems)
    • *Stemming usually refers to a crude heuristic process that chops off the ends of words in the hope of achieving this goal correctly most of the time, and often includes the removal of derivational affixes.
    • Lemmatization usually refers to doing things properly with the use of a vocabulary and morphological analysis of words, normally aiming to remove inflectional endings only and to return the base or dictionary form of a word
  • Removing stop words
  • Cleaning

Shape of the dataframe

Removing the @ and #

In [24]:
def find_hashtags(tweet):
    return " ".join([match.group(0)[1:] for match in re.finditer(r"#\w+", tweet)]) or 'no'

def find_mentions(tweet):
    return " ".join([match.group(0)[1:] for match in re.finditer(r"@\w+", tweet)]) or 'no'

def process_text(df):
    df['hashtags'] = df['text'].apply(lambda x: find_hashtags(x))
    df['mentions'] = df['text'].apply(lambda x: find_mentions(x))
    return df

train_df = process_text(train_df)
test_df = process_text(test_df)

Removing Emoji's

In [29]:
# Reference : https://gist.github.com/slowkow/7a7f61f495e3dbb7e3d767f97bd7304b
def remove_emoji(text):
    emoji_pattern = re.compile("["
                           u"\U0001F600-\U0001F64F"  # emoticons
                           u"\U0001F300-\U0001F5FF"  # symbols & pictographs
                           u"\U0001F680-\U0001F6FF"  # transport & map symbols
                           u"\U0001F1E0-\U0001F1FF"  # flags (iOS)
                           u"\U00002702-\U000027B0"
                           u"\U000024C2-\U0001F251"
                           "]+", flags=re.UNICODE)
    return emoji_pattern.sub(r'', text)

remove_emoji("Omg another Earthquake  ")

5. Visualizations¶

Class balance

In [20]:
#function to get distrubution of the cat variables
def get_distr_cat(df,feature):
    sns.set()
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
    sns.barplot(x=df[feature].value_counts().index,y=df[feature].value_counts(),palette="husl")
In [21]:
get_distr_cat(train_df,'target')

6. Count Vectorizer +Naive Bayes¶

Kaggle Accuracy Achieved: 0.77444

Bag of words approach

  • Create tokens and count of all the tokens
  • The more frequent a token is, the more important that word might be

Naive Bayes

  • Usually used with NLP problems as it's basis is in probability
  • Given a particular data how likely is a particular outcome

In [57]:
count_vectorizer=CountVectorizer(stop_words='english',min_df = 1)
#creating a bag of words vector
count_train=count_vectorizer.fit_transform(X_train)

#create bag words for testing data using same dictionary
count_test=count_vectorizer.transform(X_test)

#to get dataframe
count_train_df = pd.DataFrame(count_train.toarray(), columns=count_vectorizer.get_feature_names())
count_test_df = pd.DataFrame(count_test.toarray(), columns=count_vectorizer.get_feature_names())
In [58]:
# Mentions
vec_men = CountVectorizer(min_df = 5)
men_vec = vec_men.fit_transform(train_df['mentions'])
men_vec_test = vec_men.transform(test_df['mentions'])
X_train_men = pd.DataFrame(men_vec.toarray(), columns=vec_men.get_feature_names())
X_test_men = pd.DataFrame(men_vec_test.toarray(), columns=vec_men.get_feature_names())

# Hashtags
vec_hash = CountVectorizer(min_df = 5)
hash_vec = vec_hash.fit_transform(train_df['hashtags'])
hash_vec_test = vec_hash.transform(test_df['hashtags'])
X_train_hash = pd.DataFrame(hash_vec.toarray(), columns=vec_hash.get_feature_names())
X_test_hash = pd.DataFrame(hash_vec_test.toarray(), columns=vec_hash.get_feature_names())
print ( X_train_men.shape, X_train_hash.shape)

7. TFIDF +Naive Bayes¶

Kaggle Accuracy Achieved: 0.77076

TF-IDF : Term Frequency Inverse Document Frequency

  • Determine the most important words in each document
  • Idea: Each corpus may have more shared words than just the stopwords. These words need to be removed or down weighted in importance
  • It is given by:
  • The weight would be low if a term doesn't appear alot in the document as tf would be low, however it'll also be low if the log is close to 0 i.e. value in bracket is close to 1. So words that occour across many or all documents would have low TF-IDF weight
In [35]:
tfidf_vectorizer=TfidfVectorizer(stop_words='english')

#creating a bag of words vector
tfidf_train=tfidf_vectorizer.fit_transform(X_train)

#create bag words for testing data using same dictionary
tfidf_test=tfidf_vectorizer.transform(X_test)
